      "locked": false,
      "text": "\n\n\n\nDATABASE CORE CONCEPTS\n\nDATABASE SCHEMA GUIDELINES - \n   1. Where will my data live ? Single Database or Distributed Database - Regionalization\n   2. How will I query my data ? Based on Core entities, where I need to put my indexes on ?\n   3. Does my database require strong consistency or eventual consistency ?\n   4.  If we are seeing that we have to query multiple tables to get a single result and single table isn't useful on its own,\n       merge them as a duplicate while still having individual tables(denormalize them). While this will help with read (NO JOINS), it will increase write.\n\n\nDATABASE INDEX\n  2. Scanning database means pulling group of records (called pages) from disk into memory and then understanding if the required record \n       is present in that page. If not, continue the process with other pages.\n  3. Indexing is map of every record to which page it sits on. So, querying on index fetches the index from disk to memory and \n      then the required page which contains the record. \n  4. Five types of Index - \n           1. B+Tree data structure Index  -  B+Tree works well on equality rather than range-based query (need to retrieve a lot of pages as compared to equality).\n               A node can have many children nodes (1:M). But a node can contain a fixed number of values. Once a node overflows, the median becomes the parent and node splits.\n           2. Hash Index Data Structure (Key/value).  Hash on the index will point you to the page where records exists. - works well on equality as compared to B+Tree but \n                worse on range-based query as compared to B+Tree. \n           3. Inverted Index (Look Below)\n           4. Log Structured Merge Trees (Look Below)\n           4. Geospatial Index (Look Below)\n\n\nINDEX GUIDELINES - If your database has more 10K (magic number), propose index. Else just go with full table scan.\n        1. Hash-Index --> If you are playing with exact matches and no range-based query.\n        2. Geospatial Index --> If you are playing with location data, propose geospatial index.\n        3. Inverted Index --> If you need a read-heavy database.\n        5. Log Structured Merge Trees --> If you need a write-heavy database.\n        5. B+Tree --> your default in interviews.\n               a. If you are need indexes on multiple columns as they are always queried together - Composite Indexes work \n                 where both indexes can either show equality (birth country) or range-based (born year)\n               b. If you need to get complete data using index and don't want to query all the columns, covering index works\n                   CREATE INDEX ON TABLE(Index1, Index2) INCLUDE (<columnNames which completes the information>).\n                   Remember column names needs to be very less as it could increase index size. If it is more, better to query the table itself using index filters.\n\n\nGeoSpatial Index - \n     1. There are 3 types of Indexes - QuadTrees, R+Trees and GeoHashing.\n     2. QuadTrees and R+ Trees are like Red-Black or AVL Trees which follows binary tree structure and on every new element, it has to re-balance itself.\n         These are useful in situations where the locations are uneven distributed\n     3. On the other hand, GeoHashing follows O(1) complexity. It also follows the same logic of QuadTrees or R+ Trees on further dividing a region, but \n         it stores every location as a hash map. These are useful in even distribution.\n     \n\n\nLog Structured Merge Trees as Index\n     1. It will batch writes into memory (called memtable) and will flush to disk once memtable reached its fixed size. Additionally, it will maintain a WAL.\n     2. It is efficient for heavy writes but has a trade-off with poor reads.\n     3. Poor reads because it has first search memtable, if found, then search if there is another version of that record which is waiting to be flushed to disk\n         and then disk. It has search at all 3 places to see the recent version of the data.\n     4. It has no update policy. That means if a new update to the record comes, it will append to WAL, memtable and flush to disk and discard the old copy.\n \n\nInverted Index for Search Optimized Database (Elastic Search) -\n    1. They are useful to find list of data given a search string.\n    2. It works by using the concept of Inverted index where it breaks the statement into each word (1 word = 1 token) and \n        stem the word (such as runs or running becomes run) . \n    3. It then maps the word 'run' to the statement. So when the user searches with the string 'running', \n        it returns all the statements mapped to the word 'run'.\n\n\nCompute Server Throughput vs Storage Server Throughput vs IOPS -\n   1. Compute Server is where the database engine resides - All in memory and does not persist restart\n   2. Storage Server is where the disk actually resides.\n   3. Compute Server is connected to Storage Server using a network cable whose throughput is called \n        Compute Server throughput.\n   4. Storage Server throughput is the amount of data that server can carry to read/write from the disk.\n   5. IOPS is the number of random operations that Storage Server needs to do per sec.\n   6. Throughput = IOPS * Block Size\n   7. While throughput can be calculated via IOPS, block size may differ with respect to what data we are reading. Hence a storage server should have\n       both IOPS and throughput provided. Either of them or both of them can be a limiting factor.\n   6. Question - If a query and page lookup is 16KB each and Compute Server throughput is 594 MiB/s and \n       Storage Throughput is 125 MiB/s with 3K IOPS/sec, can the system handle 20K reads/sec ?\n          a. 1 query and 1 page lookup equates to 32KB per read. 2 operations means 2 IOPS per read.\n          b. So, 20K reads/sec means 40K IOPS/sec [beats 3K IOPS/sec]\n          c. Storage Throughput = 40K IOPS * 32KB =  1,250 MiB/s [which beats both Storage and Compute Server throughput]\n\nThere are 5 ways of scaling database - \n    1. Vertical Scaling - Give interviewers the simplest option \n    2. Proper Indexes for Read and Batch Operations to Writes or Asynchronous writes to reduce IOP\n    3. Sharding - where we separate table data into multiple database servers based on column (2 or more tables in different databases based on some column)\n    4. Partitioning -  where we separate table data in the same database server \n        Horizontal partitioning: Same columns, fewer rows per partition.\n        Vertical partitioning: Same rows, fewer columns per partition.\n    5. Replicas - creating master/slave replica of the table data in multiple database servers\n\nSharding Concept in Relational Database -\n    1. It is a horizontal scaling concept of mapping the database nodes to store a subset of user's information. \n    2. For example, if there exists a database with 100 user's information, we can divide the database into 5 database nodes\n        where node A can accept user's 0-19 request, node B can accept user's 20-39 request and so on.\n    3. It helps to scale the requests to different database nodes each containing 200 user's information instead of \n        hitting just 1 database node with 1000 user's information. \n    4. What happens if every node starts receiving more TPS than required ? We can introduce another node to take the load\n       of other nodes. However, in doing so, the request served by 1 node will now go to another node and so the data will also need to migrate.\n    5. First, We need to understand how does each node know which request to serve ? We can use the concept of hashing.\n    6. Say we if we use a hashing algorithm on the request such as `Hash(user-id) % number of nodes` \n       where we each request knows which nodes to go. \n    7. If we add an extra node, user 18 will now be served by node B and data will need to be moved. \n       This will make a cascading effect across all nodes. So, it adds an overhead every-time an extra node is added.\n    8. What if we position nodes in an uniform space and if a node gets added or removed, the other nodes don't need to move.\n       For example, if we apply hashing such as `Hash(user-id) % (2^32)`, \n        every node will receive a position in the spectrum of 0 to 2^32 - 1. Say Node A received a position 10, node B received 50.\n    9. Now if a request comes for user and if we apply the same hashing algorithm such as `Hash(user-id) % (2^32)` and the \n        result is less than 10, node A can take care of it or if the result is less than 50, node B can take care of it. \n        If the result is more than 50, node A can take care of it.\n    10. Now if a new node comes, only neighbor's data needs to be shifted rather than having a cascading effect.\n    11. This is called consistent hashing in a uniform fixed space.\n    12. To avoid having non uniform load, we can have replicas of the nodes. Every node in the hash ring can communicate with each other on the health. \n           If few replicas of a node dies, we can create replicas of other node to distribute load.\n\nMore about Sharding -\n    1. A good shard key is the one that have lots of unique values (such as user_id) to avoid uneven load \n        and a query on the database should always hit 1 shard (try to avoid cross-shard calls).\n    2. If you create a shard on country name and your users are skewed towards 1 country, that shard is likely to get hit more.\n        On the other hand, query on user_id as shard key will always hit 1 shard.\n    3. 3 types of Sharding - \n         1. Range based shard (User 1-10M in shard1, User 10M-20M in shard2)\n         2. Hash-based Sharding (the above concept)\n         3. Directory based sharding (User_id to shard_id) \n\nWriting to a hot shard (Cache or Database)\n     1. A hot shard can be further sharded into multiple instances if we are seeing high volume of writes\n         a. Use compound keys as partition keys - user_id + <timestamp>\n         b. Add randomness to partition keys - user_id + random(0,10) to be distributes to multiple shards.\n    2.  BATCHING WRITE REQUESTS: If there is no room for further sharding and there is a high volume of write influx and you don't really care about instant response,\n             a. You can add those requests to a message queue and process at its own speed.\n             b. Alternatively, you can also combine multiple requests for the same row and hit database for that entry once or twice\n                 for a fixed interval. (In-memory aggregation such as Event Processor)\n\nReading a hot shard (Cache or database)\n    1. Replicas are useful for scaling reads as well as fault-tolerance in database.\n          1. Master replica will accept write/read and slave replicas only accepts reads. \n          2. If a new data gets written to master and services require strong consistency, then all replicas needs to be updated.\n                 a. If we require partial consistency, we can think of quorum in replicas (3/5 replica needs to be updated)\n                 b. If stale data is okay to accept, the read from any replica.\n                 c. If all replica is not updated or we didn't receive a quorum, direct the reads to master till replication is complete\n .  2.  Imagine there is 100K requests per second and there is a cache miss, all 100K will hit database with the hot row (Thundering herd). In such cases, \n          a. Combine multiple requests for the same row into a single request and then hit the database with hot entry. You can also apply\n               similar pattern for a cache entry whose requests are starting to increase and you can't have more replicas. Usually cache have \n               higher throughput as compared to database\n          b. (OR) avoid cache miss by proactively updating the TTL for the hot entry or cache versioning with new TTL\n               In this way, we don't have to explicitly update the old cache entry and it will slowly gets deleted due to less frequency.\n \n\n\n\n\n",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "\n\n\n\nDATABASE CORE CONCEPTS\n\nDATABASE SCHEMA GUIDELINES - \n   1. Where will my data live ? Single Database or Distributed Database - Regionalization\n   2. How will I query my data ? Based on Core entities, where I need to put my indexes on ?\n   3. Does my database require strong consistency or eventual consistency ?\n   4.  If we are seeing that we have to query multiple tables to get a single result and single table isn't useful on its own,\n       merge them as a duplicate while still having individual tables(denormalize them). While this will help with read (NO JOINS), it will increase write.\n\n\nDATABASE INDEX\n  2. Scanning database means pulling group of records (called pages) from disk into memory and then understanding if the required record \n       is present in that page. If not, continue the process with other pages.\n  3. Indexing is map of every record to which page it sits on. So, querying on index fetches the index from disk to memory and \n      then the required page which contains the record. \n  4. Five types of Index - \n           1. B+Tree data structure Index  -  B+Tree works well on equality rather than range-based query (need to retrieve a lot of pages as compared to equality).\n               A node can have many children nodes (1:M). But a node can contain a fixed number of values. Once a node overflows, the median becomes the parent and node splits.\n           2. Hash Index Data Structure (Key/value).  Hash on the index will point you to the page where records exists. - works well on equality as compared to B+Tree but \n                worse on range-based query as compared to B+Tree. \n           3. Inverted Index (Look Below)\n           4. Log Structured Merge Trees (Look Below)\n           4. Geospatial Index (Look Below)\n\n\nINDEX GUIDELINES - If your database has more 10K (magic number), propose index. Else just go with full table scan.\n        1. Hash-Index --> If you are playing with exact matches and no range-based query.\n        2. Geospatial Index --> If you are playing with location data, propose geospatial index.\n        3. Inverted Index --> If you need a read-heavy database.\n        5. Log Structured Merge Trees --> If you need a write-heavy database.\n        5. B+Tree --> your default in interviews.\n               a. If you are need indexes on multiple columns as they are always queried together - Composite Indexes work \n                 where both indexes can either show equality (birth country) or range-based (born year)\n               b. If you need to get complete data using index and don't want to query all the columns, covering index works\n                   CREATE INDEX ON TABLE(Index1, Index2) INCLUDE (<columnNames which completes the information>).\n                   Remember column names needs to be very less as it could increase index size. If it is more, better to query the table itself using index filters.\n\n\nGeoSpatial Index - \n     1. There are 3 types of Indexes - QuadTrees, R+Trees and GeoHashing.\n     2. QuadTrees and R+ Trees are like Red-Black or AVL Trees which follows binary tree structure and on every new element, it has to re-balance itself.\n         These are useful in situations where the locations are uneven distributed\n     3. On the other hand, GeoHashing follows O(1) complexity. It also follows the same logic of QuadTrees or R+ Trees on further dividing a region, but \n         it stores every location as a hash map. These are useful in even distribution.\n     \n\n\nLog Structured Merge Trees as Index\n     1. It will batch writes into memory (called memtable) and will flush to disk once memtable reached its fixed size. Additionally, it will maintain a WAL.\n     2. It is efficient for heavy writes but has a trade-off with poor reads.\n     3. Poor reads because it has first search memtable, if found, then search if there is another version of that record which is waiting to be flushed to disk\n         and then disk. It has search at all 3 places to see the recent version of the data.\n     4. It has no update policy. That means if a new update to the record comes, it will append to WAL, memtable and flush to disk and discard the old copy.\n \n\nInverted Index for Search Optimized Database (Elastic Search) -\n    1. They are useful to find list of data given a search string.\n    2. It works by using the concept of Inverted index where it breaks the statement into each word (1 word = 1 token) and \n        stem the word (such as runs or running becomes run) . \n    3. It then maps the word 'run' to the statement. So when the user searches with the string 'running', \n        it returns all the statements mapped to the word 'run'.\n\n\nCompute Server Throughput vs Storage Server Throughput vs IOPS -\n   1. Compute Server is where the database engine resides - All in memory and does not persist restart\n   2. Storage Server is where the disk actually resides.\n   3. Compute Server is connected to Storage Server using a network cable whose throughput is called \n        Compute Server throughput.\n   4. Storage Server throughput is the amount of data that server can carry to read/write from the disk.\n   5. IOPS is the number of random operations that Storage Server needs to do per sec.\n   6. Throughput = IOPS * Block Size\n   7. While throughput can be calculated via IOPS, block size may differ with respect to what data we are reading. Hence a storage server should have\n       both IOPS and throughput provided. Either of them or both of them can be a limiting factor.\n   6. Question - If a query and page lookup is 16KB each and Compute Server throughput is 594 MiB/s and \n       Storage Throughput is 125 MiB/s with 3K IOPS/sec, can the system handle 20K reads/sec ?\n          a. 1 query and 1 page lookup equates to 32KB per read. 2 operations means 2 IOPS per read.\n          b. So, 20K reads/sec means 40K IOPS/sec [beats 3K IOPS/sec]\n          c. Storage Throughput = 40K IOPS * 32KB =  1,250 MiB/s [which beats both Storage and Compute Server throughput]\n\nThere are 5 ways of scaling database - \n    1. Vertical Scaling - Give interviewers the simplest option \n    2. Proper Indexes for Read and Batch Operations to Writes or Asynchronous writes to reduce IOP\n    3. Sharding - where we separate table data into multiple database servers based on column (2 or more tables in different databases based on some column)\n    4. Partitioning -  where we separate table data in the same database server \n        Horizontal partitioning: Same columns, fewer rows per partition.\n        Vertical partitioning: Same rows, fewer columns per partition.\n    5. Replicas - creating master/slave replica of the table data in multiple database servers\n\nSharding Concept in Relational Database -\n    1. It is a horizontal scaling concept of mapping the database nodes to store a subset of user's information. \n    2. For example, if there exists a database with 100 user's information, we can divide the database into 5 database nodes\n        where node A can accept user's 0-19 request, node B can accept user's 20-39 request and so on.\n    3. It helps to scale the requests to different database nodes each containing 200 user's information instead of \n        hitting just 1 database node with 1000 user's information. \n    4. What happens if every node starts receiving more TPS than required ? We can introduce another node to take the load\n       of other nodes. However, in doing so, the request served by 1 node will now go to another node and so the data will also need to migrate.\n    5. First, We need to understand how does each node know which request to serve ? We can use the concept of hashing.\n    6. Say we if we use a hashing algorithm on the request such as `Hash(user-id) % number of nodes` \n       where we each request knows which nodes to go. \n    7. If we add an extra node, user 18 will now be served by node B and data will need to be moved. \n       This will make a cascading effect across all nodes. So, it adds an overhead every-time an extra node is added.\n    8. What if we position nodes in an uniform space and if a node gets added or removed, the other nodes don't need to move.\n       For example, if we apply hashing such as `Hash(user-id) % (2^32)`, \n        every node will receive a position in the spectrum of 0 to 2^32 - 1. Say Node A received a position 10, node B received 50.\n    9. Now if a request comes for user and if we apply the same hashing algorithm such as `Hash(user-id) % (2^32)` and the \n        result is less than 10, node A can take care of it or if the result is less than 50, node B can take care of it. \n        If the result is more than 50, node A can take care of it.\n    10. Now if a new node comes, only neighbor's data needs to be shifted rather than having a cascading effect.\n    11. This is called consistent hashing in a uniform fixed space.\n    12. To avoid having non uniform load, we can have replicas of the nodes. Every node in the hash ring can communicate with each other on the health. \n           If few replicas of a node dies, we can create replicas of other node to distribute load.\n\nMore about Sharding -\n    1. A good shard key is the one that have lots of unique values (such as user_id) to avoid uneven load \n        and a query on the database should always hit 1 shard (try to avoid cross-shard calls).\n    2. If you create a shard on country name and your users are skewed towards 1 country, that shard is likely to get hit more.\n        On the other hand, query on user_id as shard key will always hit 1 shard.\n    3. 3 types of Sharding - \n         1. Range based shard (User 1-10M in shard1, User 10M-20M in shard2)\n         2. Hash-based Sharding (the above concept)\n         3. Directory based sharding (User_id to shard_id) \n\nWriting to a hot shard (Cache or Database)\n     1. A hot shard can be further sharded into multiple instances if we are seeing high volume of writes\n         a. Use compound keys as partition keys - user_id + <timestamp>\n         b. Add randomness to partition keys - user_id + random(0,10) to be distributes to multiple shards.\n    2.  BATCHING WRITE REQUESTS: If there is no room for further sharding and there is a high volume of write influx and you don't really care about instant response,\n             a. You can add those requests to a message queue and process at its own speed.\n             b. Alternatively, you can also combine multiple requests for the same row and hit database for that entry once or twice\n                 for a fixed interval. (In-memory aggregation such as Event Processor)\n\nReading a hot shard (Cache or database)\n    1. Replicas are useful for scaling reads as well as fault-tolerance in database.\n          1. Master replica will accept write/read and slave replicas only accepts reads. \n          2. If a new data gets written to master and services require strong consistency, then all replicas needs to be updated.\n                 a. If we require partial consistency, we can think of quorum in replicas (3/5 replica needs to be updated)\n                 b. If stale data is okay to accept, the read from any replica.\n                 c. If all replica is not updated or we didn't receive a quorum, direct the reads to master till replication is complete\n .  2.  Imagine there is 100K requests per second and there is a cache miss, all 100K will hit database with the hot row (Thundering herd). In such cases, \n          a. Combine multiple requests for the same row into a single request and then hit the database with hot entry. You can also apply\n               similar pattern for a cache entry whose requests are starting to increase and you can't have more replicas. Usually cache have \n               higher throughput as compared to database\n          b. (OR) avoid cache miss by proactively updating the TTL for the hot entry or cache versioning with new TTL\n               In this way, we don't have to explicitly update the old cache entry and it will slowly gets deleted due to less frequency.\n \n\n\n\n\n",
