      "locked": false,
      "text": "COMMON PATTERN\n\n\nHigh-frequency real-time updates where clients don't affect each other with high writes + high reads(Ad Click Analytics/ Monitoring System) \n    1. We can horizontally scale the service to increase the throughput which would involve making multiple database calls.\n    2. Bad because writing to DB for 1M clicks/ad can lead to max throughput and DB will stop responding and hence clicks will be lost.\n    3. Our requirement should be very simple - \n           a. Avoid hitting database for every click count and perform aggregation in memory.\n           b. For aggregation in memory, you need clicks for a single ad to be in same shard/server so that the aggregator can calculate \n               the count for that window and does not have to care about reading data from other shards.\n    4. We have multiple options - \n          a. SNS + SQS + Lambda + Database - If we take the FIFO approach, the throughput is 3K messages/sec. Even though we have 1 SNS + 1 SQS\n              for a single AD, clients will have operational burden to maintain this pair for every AD. Additionally, if 1 AD becomes hot (say 1M click/sec for a single ad)\n              you are gone.\n          b. DynamoDB Streams - You have to involve DynamoDB which will itself not able to handle 1M clicks/ad throughput which is roughly around\n              1 GB/sec (1 click = 1KB, hence 1M/sec * 1KB = 1GB/sec) \n          c. Kinesis + KDA - Kinesis have a max throughput of 1 GB/sec (1000 shards) which just matches the 1M clicks/sec. Here we need to make sure that partition key is ad_id\n              such that every click count for that ad goes into the same shard. Each KDA shard can listen to Kinesis stream shard which will have complete click count for the ads \n              in that Kinesis shards and it will aggregate them in memory for a fixed window and output to database.\n     5. How will we aggregate data for 1 day, 1 month or 1 year ?\n            a. We can have KDA output aggregations over a period of 1 hour to the database.\n            b. Post that, we can run cron job or aggregate when requested for a certain period.\n     6. What happens if the shard becomes hot due to popular user ? \n            a. If we are reading AD22, we can think of replicas or copying the same AD22 data in multiple shards (same data in different database servers)\n            b. If we are calculating the click count on AD22, hitting that 1 shard would be disaster. Hence, we can divide them into more shards by - \n                a. Compound keys as partition keys - 'Ad_id + timestamp' so that ('AD22 + 10PM')%2 = shard 5 is now getting hit to calculate click count.\n                b. Randomness in Partition keys - 'Ad_id + random(0, 10)' so that this ad can go to any of the shards.\n     7. What happens if you need Aggregation between ads ? (TopK Ads)\n           a. We can have CRON jobs calculating TopK periodically after Kinesis+KDA writes to the database. (OR)\n           b. Have 2 layer streaming architecture where 1st layer of Kinesis + KDA can aggregate per ad and then provide the hourly or monthly data from 1st KDA layer (all shards)\n               to just 1 shard of the 2nd KDA layer which will calculate the TopK and persist it. Similarly, we can do for monthly or daily.\n     8. For high reads during this pattern, focus on pre-computing the data as much as possible. If pre-computing fails, then compute at that instant (But call it out to interviewers)\n\nHigh-frequency real-time updates where client affect each other with high writes + high reads + Eventual Consistency (Whatsapp/LiveComments)\n    1.  In LiveComments and Whatsapp GroupChats, all the instances are publisher and subscriber so that 1 message is broadcasted to all\n         other users in real time.\n    2. Use Pub/Sub mechanism - Select a nice topic and reason about publisher/subscriber. In Direct message, \n         the receiver is the subscriber and sender is the publisher.\n    3. Remember Pub/Sub does not persist message, so there is data loss. IF data loss is a requirement, think of fallback ways (inbox in whatsapp)\n    4. For high writes, focus on the above strategy of using a streaming layer.\n    5. Since users and servers both send message to each other, focus on  bi-directional communication (web socket).\n\nHigh-frequency real time updates where client affect each other with high writes + high reads + Eventual Consistency (Quip docs) -\n    1. Follow the protocol of upload and then download.\n    2. Clients and server maintain data separately and server owns the responsibility of resolving the conflicts - \n           a.  Client 1 and Client 2 uploads its data to the server which routes it to Conflict Resolution Server\n           b. The server will compare the timestamp and resolve the conflict of making Client 1's chunk as the official copy.\n           c. Once the server publishes the message to Pub/Sub, it is broadcasted to all instances and the instances sends the information to clients.\n           d. Client 1 will compare and find the data's lastUpdatedTimestamp in its local DB is equal to that of server copy and won't do anything.\n           3. Client 2 will compare and find the chunk's lastUpdatedTimestamp in its local DB is less than that of server copy and will download the chunk.\n\nHigh-frequency real time updates where client affect each other with high writes + high reads + Strong Consistency (AuctionBidding) -\n    1. Follow the principle of using Pub/Sub once a bid is finalized, broadcast to other server instances.\n    2. For high writes with strong consistency, make sure to use the principle of distributed lock but keep an eye on the throughput.\n    3. If the writes keep on increasing, shard the server based on item_id and keep 1 distributed lock instance per item_id at max of 100K.\n    4. If the writes to a single item keep on increasing, then make a trade-off of rate-limiting or bid may be accepted or rejected for assessment.\n\nCompeting for a single resource (Buying Tickets/Grocery Shopping/Auction Bidding)\n      1. If all the users are connected to the same server fighting for the same ticket seat, always start with application level locking (mutex for atomic operation).\n      2. If you don't want application level locking and comfortable with database level locking, there are 2 ways in SQL -\n              a. Optimistic concurrency control includes version numbers or expected values in updates (Conflicts are rare)\n              b. Pessimistic concurrency control locks the row BEFORE reading the value and then proceed to update.\n                  Helpful to avoid conflicts after reading but before writing (Conflicts are frequent)\n      3. If multiple users are connected to multiple servers, every server will contact the database once to buy the tickets and it can lead to double booking.\n          In such cases, we can have 2 options - \n              a. We can have strongly consistent distributed locks. Now, what if all the servers make a call to distributed locks at once for a very popular concert, \n                  we need to hit the distributed lock in a sequential manner so that 1 request can set the lock with TTL and other gracefully see that value and return.\n              b. Request all the servers to send the write call to a message broker specifically designed for that concert and that first one out will update the database\n                  and the others will update the same seat but the seat status could be 'RESERVED'.\n              c. Option b is less favorable because an event can become hot during runtime and we don't want to spin up a infrastructure and make code changes. Additionally, \n                  you have to maintain different seat status for a ticket because users may need some time to complete booking information. This seat status can be completely \n                  eliminated with distributed locks because a locking would entail it is reserved so that other users cannot see them. Once the user confirms the seat, the database\n                  is modified to complete.\n      4. In case where you need to update multiple databases (Debit/Credit between 2 accounts), prefer to lock in a fixed manner always irrespective of which account is sending the payment\n              a. If both the users are connected to same server and prefer application level tracking, remember you need to persist what you do so that you can recover from failure and proceed\n                  to database transaction in a fixed manner\n              b. If both the users are connected to different server, use distributed locks in a fixed manner\n              c. #a and #b will help in avoiding deadlock\n       5. Since now, we establish distributed lock as a mechanism to compete for a resource (strong consistency) when users are connected to different servers - \n              a. We can use distributed lock if the count of the resource is always 1. But this is not the case in majority of things \n                  such as grocery inventory (2 step action - reserve and purchase) or bidding for an item (1 step action - validate if bid is greater)\n              b. In such cases, we can use <item_id>:<count> --> This will be useful for total count of an item or bid price of an item.\n              c. For reservation, we can use <item_id_user_id_reserver>:<count>. In such cases, we need to update the total count of the item.\n              d. Step b and Step c needs to be atomic in nature.\n              e. In short, we are using cache as a lock interchangeably and DISTRIBUTED CACHE acts a source of truth which helps in reading faster \n\nHigh-frequency real-time updates where clients only reads and does not affect other clients (StockUpdate)\n    1. Always use Pub/Sub mechanism by selecting a nice topic . \n    2. Only 1 publisher but multiple subscribers\n    3. All of the server will maintain SSE connection.\n\n\nUpload large file (>10MB) to S3 storage\n    1. I want to upload photos via Amazon Photos. Amazon Photos app is my client and there is backend server which uses S3 as cloud storage.\n    2. When I want to upload a photo, the app (client) will make a request to backend server which will return a pre-signed URL and save metadata\n        information in the database.\n    3. The app will directly upload the attachment to S3, where S3 will validate the pre-signed URL.\n    4. When I want to view the photo in my app, the app will send a request to server which will return the Content Deliver Network URL (AWS Cloud Front)\n        to the app.\n    5. The app will proceed to connect with CDN to fetch the photo. If the CDN does not have the image in the cache, it will retrieve the pre-signed URL\n         from the CDN URL and make a call to S3 to download the image, cache it and then return it to the app.\n        \n\nUploading a large file (>10MB) with resume-able upload/download \n    1. Amazon Photos app needs to upload a 5GB file. The app takes the responsibility of splitting the large file using SPLIT command into smaller chunks say 5MB. \n        You can also use AWS Client SDK which will take care of stripping as well as generating a unique fingerprint for every chunk\n    2. The app will persist all of these chunks metadata in its local DB and make a request to server to upload this large file by providing all the chunk metadata.\n    3. The server will persist all the chunk metadata to the file-id in its DB and would provide pre-signed URL for all the chunks to the app.\n    4. The app will start uploading the chunk to S3 and on completion will update its local and SERVER DB accordingly with progress metadata and timestamp\n        to avoid single point of failure if device crashes\n    5. If the network connection breaks, the app knows till what chunk it uploaded and S3 will have partial data.\n    6. Once the network resumes, the app will start uploading the remaining chunk to S3. Once it completes, it sends a request to server with updated chunk\n        metadata and the server sends a completion request to S3 stating that upload is complete. Post that S3 internally consolidates the chunk to make it a big file.\n            a. To guarantee correctness, the server and S3 can have a notification queue which says that a chunk has been uploaded and the server should update the \n                metadata in its backend. In this way, the app need not send all the progress metadata of the all the chunks at Step 6. \n                The app can only send that it is done, so that the server can say the same to S3. \n    7. Now, we need to download the photo. The app makes a request to server which provides with CDN URL (it has pre-signed S3 URL)\n    8. The app keeps a track of what portion of the file has been download. CDN and S3 does not know what part of the data has been downloaded.\n    9. If the network breaks and resumes, the app needs to specify the range to be downloaded from CDN.\n          a. GET /large-file.zip\n              Range: bytes=0-10485759  (first 10MB)\n   10. If the local and server has FileCHUNKMETADATA table for every file, we can proceed with delta sync where we can identify which CHUNKS are NEW and which got\n          DELETED, so that only those can be updated across devices.\n\n\nMulti-Step Workflow (E-commerce)\n      1. All Orders looks like a finite state machine (Order Placed - Inventory Update - Payment - Confirmation)\n      2. All the state transitions for each order needs to be persisted in the event of crash\n      3. There could be multiple instances of the workers working for same state to transition an order to that state to new state. For example, multiple instances of the payment workers\n           will pick up the orders sitting in Payment state, talk to payment service, if succeeded, transition to confirmation state, where confirmation workers will confirm to the user\n          Else failed state where failure workers send a rejection email to users.\n\n\nLong Running Tasks (Trans-coding for youtube video)\n     1. For tasks which require a lot of computational power and is a long running process, the server should put the task in a queue, update its database \n         and reply back to the client that is is ongoing.\n     2. A lambda worker (from multiple instances) will read from the queue, execute the task and update the server's database.\n     3. The server database can then notify the server that task has been completed, to which server can respond to the client. \n     4. The server-client communication could SSE or web-socket.\n     5. Since we have bunch of lambda workers (stateless), we ideally should maintain a heartbeat mechanism so that we can spawn a new one but AWS handles\n         auto-scaling.\n     6. You can also separate queues based on approximate task type (Generating a report takes 5 seconds where transcoding may take 1 hour)\n     7. For these 1 hour tasks, we may need to implement the multi-step-workflow - prefer server to own the responsibility of finite state machine for that job\n         and break the job into smaller parts for easy and shorter processing.\n\n\nScaling Reads -\n    1. Replicas of database shards\n    2. Pre-computed cache and then on-demand cache\n    3. Replica of hot shard containing hot data - \n\nScaling writes - \n   1. Queue/Aggregate them up to control writes to database\n   2. Create more shards for hot data \n     \n     ",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "COMMON PATTERN\n\n\nHigh-frequency real-time updates where clients don't affect each other with high writes + high reads(Ad Click Analytics/ Monitoring System) \n    1. We can horizontally scale the service to increase the throughput which would involve making multiple database calls.\n    2. Bad because writing to DB for 1M clicks/ad can lead to max throughput and DB will stop responding and hence clicks will be lost.\n    3. Our requirement should be very simple - \n           a. Avoid hitting database for every click count and perform aggregation in memory.\n           b. For aggregation in memory, you need clicks for a single ad to be in same shard/server so that the aggregator can calculate \n               the count for that window and does not have to care about reading data from other shards.\n    4. We have multiple options - \n          a. SNS + SQS + Lambda + Database - If we take the FIFO approach, the throughput is 3K messages/sec. Even though we have 1 SNS + 1 SQS\n              for a single AD, clients will have operational burden to maintain this pair for every AD. Additionally, if 1 AD becomes hot (say 1M click/sec for a single ad)\n              you are gone.\n          b. DynamoDB Streams - You have to involve DynamoDB which will itself not able to handle 1M clicks/ad throughput which is roughly around\n              1 GB/sec (1 click = 1KB, hence 1M/sec * 1KB = 1GB/sec) \n          c. Kinesis + KDA - Kinesis have a max throughput of 1 GB/sec (1000 shards) which just matches the 1M clicks/sec. Here we need to make sure that partition key is ad_id\n              such that every click count for that ad goes into the same shard. Each KDA shard can listen to Kinesis stream shard which will have complete click count for the ads \n              in that Kinesis shards and it will aggregate them in memory for a fixed window and output to database.\n     5. How will we aggregate data for 1 day, 1 month or 1 year ?\n            a. We can have KDA output aggregations over a period of 1 hour to the database.\n            b. Post that, we can run cron job or aggregate when requested for a certain period.\n     6. What happens if the shard becomes hot due to popular user ? \n            a. If we are reading AD22, we can think of replicas or copying the same AD22 data in multiple shards (same data in different database servers)\n            b. If we are calculating the click count on AD22, hitting that 1 shard would be disaster. Hence, we can divide them into more shards by - \n                a. Compound keys as partition keys - 'Ad_id + timestamp' so that ('AD22 + 10PM')%2 = shard 5 is now getting hit to calculate click count.\n                b. Randomness in Partition keys - 'Ad_id + random(0, 10)' so that this ad can go to any of the shards.\n     7. What happens if you need Aggregation between ads ? (TopK Ads)\n           a. We can have CRON jobs calculating TopK periodically after Kinesis+KDA writes to the database. (OR)\n           b. Have 2 layer streaming architecture where 1st layer of Kinesis + KDA can aggregate per ad and then provide the hourly or monthly data from 1st KDA layer (all shards)\n               to just 1 shard of the 2nd KDA layer which will calculate the TopK and persist it. Similarly, we can do for monthly or daily.\n     8. For high reads during this pattern, focus on pre-computing the data as much as possible. If pre-computing fails, then compute at that instant (But call it out to interviewers)\n\nHigh-frequency real-time updates where client affect each other with high writes + high reads + Eventual Consistency (Whatsapp/LiveComments)\n    1.  In LiveComments and Whatsapp GroupChats, all the instances are publisher and subscriber so that 1 message is broadcasted to all\n         other users in real time.\n    2. Use Pub/Sub mechanism - Select a nice topic and reason about publisher/subscriber. In Direct message, \n         the receiver is the subscriber and sender is the publisher.\n    3. Remember Pub/Sub does not persist message, so there is data loss. IF data loss is a requirement, think of fallback ways (inbox in whatsapp)\n    4. For high writes, focus on the above strategy of using a streaming layer.\n    5. Since users and servers both send message to each other, focus on  bi-directional communication (web socket).\n\nHigh-frequency real time updates where client affect each other with high writes + high reads + Eventual Consistency (Quip docs) -\n    1. Follow the protocol of upload and then download.\n    2. Clients and server maintain data separately and server owns the responsibility of resolving the conflicts - \n           a.  Client 1 and Client 2 uploads its data to the server which routes it to Conflict Resolution Server\n           b. The server will compare the timestamp and resolve the conflict of making Client 1's chunk as the official copy.\n           c. Once the server publishes the message to Pub/Sub, it is broadcasted to all instances and the instances sends the information to clients.\n           d. Client 1 will compare and find the data's lastUpdatedTimestamp in its local DB is equal to that of server copy and won't do anything.\n           3. Client 2 will compare and find the chunk's lastUpdatedTimestamp in its local DB is less than that of server copy and will download the chunk.\n\nHigh-frequency real time updates where client affect each other with high writes + high reads + Strong Consistency (AuctionBidding) -\n    1. Follow the principle of using Pub/Sub once a bid is finalized, broadcast to other server instances.\n    2. For high writes with strong consistency, make sure to use the principle of distributed lock but keep an eye on the throughput.\n    3. If the writes keep on increasing, shard the server based on item_id and keep 1 distributed lock instance per item_id at max of 100K.\n    4. If the writes to a single item keep on increasing, then make a trade-off of rate-limiting or bid may be accepted or rejected for assessment.\n\nCompeting for a single resource (Buying Tickets/Grocery Shopping/Auction Bidding)\n      1. If all the users are connected to the same server fighting for the same ticket seat, always start with application level locking (mutex for atomic operation).\n      2. If you don't want application level locking and comfortable with database level locking, there are 2 ways in SQL -\n              a. Optimistic concurrency control includes version numbers or expected values in updates (Conflicts are rare)\n              b. Pessimistic concurrency control locks the row BEFORE reading the value and then proceed to update.\n                  Helpful to avoid conflicts after reading but before writing (Conflicts are frequent)\n      3. If multiple users are connected to multiple servers, every server will contact the database once to buy the tickets and it can lead to double booking.\n          In such cases, we can have 2 options - \n              a. We can have strongly consistent distributed locks. Now, what if all the servers make a call to distributed locks at once for a very popular concert, \n                  we need to hit the distributed lock in a sequential manner so that 1 request can set the lock with TTL and other gracefully see that value and return.\n              b. Request all the servers to send the write call to a message broker specifically designed for that concert and that first one out will update the database\n                  and the others will update the same seat but the seat status could be 'RESERVED'.\n              c. Option b is less favorable because an event can become hot during runtime and we don't want to spin up a infrastructure and make code changes. Additionally, \n                  you have to maintain different seat status for a ticket because users may need some time to complete booking information. This seat status can be completely \n                  eliminated with distributed locks because a locking would entail it is reserved so that other users cannot see them. Once the user confirms the seat, the database\n                  is modified to complete.\n      4. In case where you need to update multiple databases (Debit/Credit between 2 accounts), prefer to lock in a fixed manner always irrespective of which account is sending the payment\n              a. If both the users are connected to same server and prefer application level tracking, remember you need to persist what you do so that you can recover from failure and proceed\n                  to database transaction in a fixed manner\n              b. If both the users are connected to different server, use distributed locks in a fixed manner\n              c. #a and #b will help in avoiding deadlock\n       5. Since now, we establish distributed lock as a mechanism to compete for a resource (strong consistency) when users are connected to different servers - \n              a. We can use distributed lock if the count of the resource is always 1. But this is not the case in majority of things \n                  such as grocery inventory (2 step action - reserve and purchase) or bidding for an item (1 step action - validate if bid is greater)\n              b. In such cases, we can use <item_id>:<count> --> This will be useful for total count of an item or bid price of an item.\n              c. For reservation, we can use <item_id_user_id_reserver>:<count>. In such cases, we need to update the total count of the item.\n              d. Step b and Step c needs to be atomic in nature.\n              e. In short, we are using cache as a lock interchangeably and DISTRIBUTED CACHE acts a source of truth which helps in reading faster \n\nHigh-frequency real-time updates where clients only reads and does not affect other clients (StockUpdate)\n    1. Always use Pub/Sub mechanism by selecting a nice topic . \n    2. Only 1 publisher but multiple subscribers\n    3. All of the server will maintain SSE connection.\n\n\nUpload large file (>10MB) to S3 storage\n    1. I want to upload photos via Amazon Photos. Amazon Photos app is my client and there is backend server which uses S3 as cloud storage.\n    2. When I want to upload a photo, the app (client) will make a request to backend server which will return a pre-signed URL and save metadata\n        information in the database.\n    3. The app will directly upload the attachment to S3, where S3 will validate the pre-signed URL.\n    4. When I want to view the photo in my app, the app will send a request to server which will return the Content Deliver Network URL (AWS Cloud Front)\n        to the app.\n    5. The app will proceed to connect with CDN to fetch the photo. If the CDN does not have the image in the cache, it will retrieve the pre-signed URL\n         from the CDN URL and make a call to S3 to download the image, cache it and then return it to the app.\n        \n\nUploading a large file (>10MB) with resume-able upload/download \n    1. Amazon Photos app needs to upload a 5GB file. The app takes the responsibility of splitting the large file using SPLIT command into smaller chunks say 5MB. \n        You can also use AWS Client SDK which will take care of stripping as well as generating a unique fingerprint for every chunk\n    2. The app will persist all of these chunks metadata in its local DB and make a request to server to upload this large file by providing all the chunk metadata.\n    3. The server will persist all the chunk metadata to the file-id in its DB and would provide pre-signed URL for all the chunks to the app.\n    4. The app will start uploading the chunk to S3 and on completion will update its local and SERVER DB accordingly with progress metadata and timestamp\n        to avoid single point of failure if device crashes\n    5. If the network connection breaks, the app knows till what chunk it uploaded and S3 will have partial data.\n    6. Once the network resumes, the app will start uploading the remaining chunk to S3. Once it completes, it sends a request to server with updated chunk\n        metadata and the server sends a completion request to S3 stating that upload is complete. Post that S3 internally consolidates the chunk to make it a big file.\n            a. To guarantee correctness, the server and S3 can have a notification queue which says that a chunk has been uploaded and the server should update the \n                metadata in its backend. In this way, the app need not send all the progress metadata of the all the chunks at Step 6. \n                The app can only send that it is done, so that the server can say the same to S3. \n    7. Now, we need to download the photo. The app makes a request to server which provides with CDN URL (it has pre-signed S3 URL)\n    8. The app keeps a track of what portion of the file has been download. CDN and S3 does not know what part of the data has been downloaded.\n    9. If the network breaks and resumes, the app needs to specify the range to be downloaded from CDN.\n          a. GET /large-file.zip\n              Range: bytes=0-10485759  (first 10MB)\n   10. If the local and server has FileCHUNKMETADATA table for every file, we can proceed with delta sync where we can identify which CHUNKS are NEW and which got\n          DELETED, so that only those can be updated across devices.\n\n\nMulti-Step Workflow (E-commerce)\n      1. All Orders looks like a finite state machine (Order Placed - Inventory Update - Payment - Confirmation)\n      2. All the state transitions for each order needs to be persisted in the event of crash\n      3. There could be multiple instances of the workers working for same state to transition an order to that state to new state. For example, multiple instances of the payment workers\n           will pick up the orders sitting in Payment state, talk to payment service, if succeeded, transition to confirmation state, where confirmation workers will confirm to the user\n          Else failed state where failure workers send a rejection email to users.\n\n\nLong Running Tasks (Trans-coding for youtube video)\n     1. For tasks which require a lot of computational power and is a long running process, the server should put the task in a queue, update its database \n         and reply back to the client that is is ongoing.\n     2. A lambda worker (from multiple instances) will read from the queue, execute the task and update the server's database.\n     3. The server database can then notify the server that task has been completed, to which server can respond to the client. \n     4. The server-client communication could SSE or web-socket.\n     5. Since we have bunch of lambda workers (stateless), we ideally should maintain a heartbeat mechanism so that we can spawn a new one but AWS handles\n         auto-scaling.\n     6. You can also separate queues based on approximate task type (Generating a report takes 5 seconds where transcoding may take 1 hour)\n     7. For these 1 hour tasks, we may need to implement the multi-step-workflow - prefer server to own the responsibility of finite state machine for that job\n         and break the job into smaller parts for easy and shorter processing.\n\n\nScaling Reads -\n    1. Replicas of database shards\n    2. Pre-computed cache and then on-demand cache\n    3. Replica of hot shard containing hot data - \n\nScaling writes - \n   1. Queue/Aggregate them up to control writes to database\n   2. Create more shards for hot data \n     \n     ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
