      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b2U",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1662214631,
      "version": 11428,
      "versionNonce": 501895017,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1766856842800,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Facebook News Feed\n\nFunctional Requirement - \n    1. User should be able to create a post with images/videos/text.\n    2. Users should be able to follow people\n    3. All the Followers of that user should be able to view the post in their news feed\n    4. Users should be able to scroll their feed indefinitely.\n\nNon-Functional Requirement - \n    1. User should be able to create a post in near real time (< 100ms)\n    2. User should be able to follow people instantly (< 100 ms)\n    3. The Feed generation should be in real time (< 100ms)\n    4. The system should prioritize availability.\n    5. Consider 2B people, expect 20K posts/sec and 20K feeds/sec\n\nAPI Contracts -\n\n1. POST /create/\n    {\n         userId:\n         Caption:\n         Text:\n          AttachmentsPresent: true/falase\n          Timestamp\n    }\n     \n     {\n           postId:\n           S3Url:\n           Timestamp\n     }\n\n2. POST /follow/ --> confirmationId and status code 200\n     {\n           userId\n           followedUserId\n           timestamp\n     }\n\n3. GET /feed?LastRefreshedTimestamp={}&last_feed_id={}&count={}\n     \n    Array of {\n          userId\n          Caption\n          Text\n          S3Url\n          CreationTimestamp\n          TotalComments\n          TotalLikes\n     }\n\nHigh Level Design\n\n1. Users should be able to create posts\n      a. App1 sends a request to 'PostCreation' Microservice which creates a record in the POST table.\n      b. Is the request has AttachmentsPresent as true, the microservice provides a generated S3 pre-signed URL\n          to the App to upload the image.\n      c. Once the image/video is downloaded, it makes a PATCH request to the same microservice with the postId\n          and the microservice update the statusOfAttachment.\n\n2. Users should be able to follow other users\n     a. App1 sends a request to 'Follow' microservice which first makes a record of the follow request in the FOLLOW\n         table with status as 'RequestSent'. \n     b. Once the record is created, it queries the deviceList from the USER table via the followed user id and sents a\n         device push notification to the IP address of all the devices that user is logged in.\n\n3. Users should be able to see his feed\n    a. App1 make a request to view the feed via the 'Feed' microservice which queries the list of userId that the user follows\n        via the FOLLOW table.\n    b. For all the users, the Feed micorservice queries the list of posts and returns to the App1.\n    c. At this moment, neither the feed generation is in real time and neither the list of posts is paginated which will cause a trouble in \n        sending response as it may be bigger than HTTP payload.\n\n4. Users should be able to scroll their feed indefinitely.\n    a. The App does not require all the posts to be sent by the Feed micro-service.\n    b.  Hence, App will sent a GET request based on refreshedTimestamp (the timestamp at which App1 generated its first feed), last_feed_id be 0 \n        and count as 50.\n    c. The Feed microservice will query the FOLLOW table to provide the list of followed userId where timestamp <= lastRefreshedTimestamp\n        and then query the list of records from POST table with LIMIT of 50 WHERE creation timestamp <= lastRefreshedTimestamp\n         sort by creation timestamp dec\n    d. The App1 should proactively sense that the user is soon to be run out of posts. So, probably at 30th post, the app should make another \n         GET request to the Feed microservice with the same Refreshed Timestamp, last_feed_id as 49th Post and count as 50.\n    e. The Feed microservice will again query the list of followed user id from the FOLLOW table where timestamp <= lastRefreshedTimestamp\n         and then query the list of records from POST table with LIMIT 50, WHERE post.id <= last_feed_id AND creation timestamp <= lastRefreshedTimestamp\n         sort by creation timestamp dec.\n    f.  The first GET call will take time more than our threshold. However, for the subsequent GET calls, if the app can proactively sense, then the time\n         required by GET call will still be same but the user will able to see his post 50th to post 99th in about real time.\n\n\n5. Users should be able to view their feed instantly in real time (< 100ms)\n     a. For reads to be instantaneous, we need to pre-compute the feed generation.\n     b. For pre-compute, we need some type of cache which the Feed microservice can query via memory.\n     c. Since the App only requests for first 50 whenever the user request for its feed initially, it makes sense for cache to have size 50. \n     d. We can use a Redis Sorted Set which will keep on sorting the Cache by creation timestamp.\n     e. We need the cache to behave like Deque where newly created post sits at the front and old created posts should get removed from the bottom\n     f. To fill up the cache, we can use the PostCreation service to do some asynchronous work.\n     g. Once the post is created, we can ask the microservice to put the post metadata in SQS which will be consumed by Lambda.\n     h. The lambda will have the below responsibilities - \n             a. It will query the list of users which follows the current author of the post via the FOLLOW table.\n             b. For every user which follows the author, the lambda will add it to their cache.\n             c. Since the cache is a sorted set based on creation timestamp, the newly added cache will always sit at top.\n     i. Now, the pagination workflow will differ - \n            a.  App will sent a GET request based on refreshedTimestamp (the timestamp at which App1 generated its first feed), last_feed_id be 0 and count as 50.\n            b. The Feed microservice will query the Cache immediately and return it to the user under 100ms.\n            c. Now, the App should still be proactive in sensing when the user will run out of content. So, when the second call is being made, the microservice\n                can fallback to the previous mechanism of querying the FOLLOW table and get the list of users that the user follows \n                and then query the list of records from POST table with LIMIT 50, WHERE post.id <= last_feed_id AND creation timestamp <= lastRefreshedTimestamp\n                sort by creation timestamp desc.\n            d. Now the second call will not be in real time but to the user it will feel as real time because we are proactively fetching the page and caching it in the App.\n     j. For celebrity users which are users with followers over 100K, the lambda will un-necessarily bombard all the 100K cache with the new posts.\n     k. So, the idea of pre-computed cache always looks good for users with less followers. In this interview, we are using 100K as threshold.\n     l. Now, if the Users which follows celebrity as well as non-celebrity, the Feed micro-service will query the cache for non-celebrity\n        and return it to the users.\n     m. In the background, it can make a database query to FOLLOW table to identify the list of celebrities the user follows and retrieve their posts\n        and send it additionally on top of requested 50.\n     n. Now, it is a business decision to should the celebrity post at top or now. For celebrity posts, I think the main bottleneck \n          is to find the number of followers of every followed user by the current user and see if their number of followers\n          is above a specific threshold. All of these queries can be avoided if we can pre-compute the list of celebrities an user follows when they hit the Follow button.\n     o. If we need to show them at top, we can have a cache per user to maintain the list of celebrities which they follow. \n          The Feed microservice can just query the user_id and check if there are any new posts from them. If yes, retrieve them and add it to the top of SortedSet of non-celebrity users.\n\nHow can be handle 20K posts/sec and 20K feed/sec ?\n     1. The cache, SQS and Lambda can handle 20K reads/sec and 20K writes/sec. We are only using cache for reading the top 50 posts. Post that, we will proceed with database queries.\n     2. Database cannot handle 20K writes and neither 20K reads at sec.\n     3. Let's analyze the tables first - USER and FOLLOW table will most likely have less writes as compared to POST table. So, lets separate them out in different database.\n     4. For USER and FOLLOW, we can have relational database. On the other hand, POST table can also have relational or non-relational database.\n     5. Keeping it simple, lets say both the databases are relational database.\n     6. Now, POST table can have viral contents which are read a lot of times as compared to other posts.\n     7. In such scenarios, database can be shard by post_id. If I shard by user_id, a single celebrity who is viral at the moment can bombard that database instance.\n     8. Hence, we can proceed with caution and shard by post_id. If that 1 viral celebrity posts multiple posts, the loadf can be shared by multiple database instances.\n     9. Considering viral contents are posted by celebrities, we can think of a strategy to have bunch of instances for celebrity posts. \n         Those instances needs a very high read throughput. Based on estimations from peak day, we can think of adding more replicas to those celebrity shard instances.\n     10. If adding replicas is not making a certain host worn out, we can also think of migrating that post to a lesser load database or add more replicas.\n     11. For database having posts of non-celebrity, we can shard by user_id but we might not need replicas for the same.\n    \n   \n    ",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Facebook News Feed\n\nFunctional Requirement - \n    1. User should be able to create a post with images/videos/text.\n    2. Users should be able to follow people\n    3. All the Followers of that user should be able to view the post in their news feed\n    4. Users should be able to scroll their feed indefinitely.\n\nNon-Functional Requirement - \n    1. User should be able to create a post in near real time (< 100ms)\n    2. User should be able to follow people instantly (< 100 ms)\n    3. The Feed generation should be in real time (< 100ms)\n    4. The system should prioritize availability.\n    5. Consider 2B people, expect 20K posts/sec and 20K feeds/sec\n\nAPI Contracts -\n\n1. POST /create/\n    {\n         userId:\n         Caption:\n         Text:\n          AttachmentsPresent: true/falase\n          Timestamp\n    }\n     \n     {\n           postId:\n           S3Url:\n           Timestamp\n     }\n\n2. POST /follow/ --> confirmationId and status code 200\n     {\n           userId\n           followedUserId\n           timestamp\n     }\n\n3. GET /feed?LastRefreshedTimestamp={}&last_feed_id={}&count={}\n     \n    Array of {\n          userId\n          Caption\n          Text\n          S3Url\n          CreationTimestamp\n          TotalComments\n          TotalLikes\n     }\n\nHigh Level Design\n\n1. Users should be able to create posts\n      a. App1 sends a request to 'PostCreation' Microservice which creates a record in the POST table.\n      b. Is the request has AttachmentsPresent as true, the microservice provides a generated S3 pre-signed URL\n          to the App to upload the image.\n      c. Once the image/video is downloaded, it makes a PATCH request to the same microservice with the postId\n          and the microservice update the statusOfAttachment.\n\n2. Users should be able to follow other users\n     a. App1 sends a request to 'Follow' microservice which first makes a record of the follow request in the FOLLOW\n         table with status as 'RequestSent'. \n     b. Once the record is created, it queries the deviceList from the USER table via the followed user id and sents a\n         device push notification to the IP address of all the devices that user is logged in.\n\n3. Users should be able to see his feed\n    a. App1 make a request to view the feed via the 'Feed' microservice which queries the list of userId that the user follows\n        via the FOLLOW table.\n    b. For all the users, the Feed micorservice queries the list of posts and returns to the App1.\n    c. At this moment, neither the feed generation is in real time and neither the list of posts is paginated which will cause a trouble in \n        sending response as it may be bigger than HTTP payload.\n\n4. Users should be able to scroll their feed indefinitely.\n    a. The App does not require all the posts to be sent by the Feed micro-service.\n    b.  Hence, App will sent a GET request based on refreshedTimestamp (the timestamp at which App1 generated its first feed), last_feed_id be 0 \n        and count as 50.\n    c. The Feed microservice will query the FOLLOW table to provide the list of followed userId where timestamp <= lastRefreshedTimestamp\n        and then query the list of records from POST table with LIMIT of 50 WHERE creation timestamp <= lastRefreshedTimestamp\n         sort by creation timestamp dec\n    d. The App1 should proactively sense that the user is soon to be run out of posts. So, probably at 30th post, the app should make another \n         GET request to the Feed microservice with the same Refreshed Timestamp, last_feed_id as 49th Post and count as 50.\n    e. The Feed microservice will again query the list of followed user id from the FOLLOW table where timestamp <= lastRefreshedTimestamp\n         and then query the list of records from POST table with LIMIT 50, WHERE post.id <= last_feed_id AND creation timestamp <= lastRefreshedTimestamp\n         sort by creation timestamp dec.\n    f.  The first GET call will take time more than our threshold. However, for the subsequent GET calls, if the app can proactively sense, then the time\n         required by GET call will still be same but the user will able to see his post 50th to post 99th in about real time.\n\n\n5. Users should be able to view their feed instantly in real time (< 100ms)\n     a. For reads to be instantaneous, we need to pre-compute the feed generation.\n     b. For pre-compute, we need some type of cache which the Feed microservice can query via memory.\n     c. Since the App only requests for first 50 whenever the user request for its feed initially, it makes sense for cache to have size 50. \n     d. We can use a Redis Sorted Set which will keep on sorting the Cache by creation timestamp.\n     e. We need the cache to behave like Deque where newly created post sits at the front and old created posts should get removed from the bottom\n     f. To fill up the cache, we can use the PostCreation service to do some asynchronous work.\n     g. Once the post is created, we can ask the microservice to put the post metadata in SQS which will be consumed by Lambda.\n     h. The lambda will have the below responsibilities - \n             a. It will query the list of users which follows the current author of the post via the FOLLOW table.\n             b. For every user which follows the author, the lambda will add it to their cache.\n             c. Since the cache is a sorted set based on creation timestamp, the newly added cache will always sit at top.\n     i. Now, the pagination workflow will differ - \n            a.  App will sent a GET request based on refreshedTimestamp (the timestamp at which App1 generated its first feed), last_feed_id be 0 and count as 50.\n            b. The Feed microservice will query the Cache immediately and return it to the user under 100ms.\n            c. Now, the App should still be proactive in sensing when the user will run out of content. So, when the second call is being made, the microservice\n                can fallback to the previous mechanism of querying the FOLLOW table and get the list of users that the user follows \n                and then query the list of records from POST table with LIMIT 50, WHERE post.id <= last_feed_id AND creation timestamp <= lastRefreshedTimestamp\n                sort by creation timestamp desc.\n            d. Now the second call will not be in real time but to the user it will feel as real time because we are proactively fetching the page and caching it in the App.\n     j. For celebrity users which are users with followers over 100K, the lambda will un-necessarily bombard all the 100K cache with the new posts.\n     k. So, the idea of pre-computed cache always looks good for users with less followers. In this interview, we are using 100K as threshold.\n     l. Now, if the Users which follows celebrity as well as non-celebrity, the Feed micro-service will query the cache for non-celebrity\n        and return it to the users.\n     m. In the background, it can make a database query to FOLLOW table to identify the list of celebrities the user follows and retrieve their posts\n        and send it additionally on top of requested 50.\n     n. Now, it is a business decision to should the celebrity post at top or now. For celebrity posts, I think the main bottleneck \n          is to find the number of followers of every followed user by the current user and see if their number of followers\n          is above a specific threshold. All of these queries can be avoided if we can pre-compute the list of celebrities an user follows when they hit the Follow button.\n     o. If we need to show them at top, we can have a cache per user to maintain the list of celebrities which they follow. \n          The Feed microservice can just query the user_id and check if there are any new posts from them. If yes, retrieve them and add it to the top of SortedSet of non-celebrity users.\n\nHow can be handle 20K posts/sec and 20K feed/sec ?\n     1. The cache, SQS and Lambda can handle 20K reads/sec and 20K writes/sec. We are only using cache for reading the top 50 posts. Post that, we will proceed with database queries.\n     2. Database cannot handle 20K writes and neither 20K reads at sec.\n     3. Let's analyze the tables first - USER and FOLLOW table will most likely have less writes as compared to POST table. So, lets separate them out in different database.\n     4. For USER and FOLLOW, we can have relational database. On the other hand, POST table can also have relational or non-relational database.\n     5. Keeping it simple, lets say both the databases are relational database.\n     6. Now, POST table can have viral contents which are read a lot of times as compared to other posts.\n     7. In such scenarios, database can be shard by post_id. If I shard by user_id, a single celebrity who is viral at the moment can bombard that database instance.\n     8. Hence, we can proceed with caution and shard by post_id. If that 1 viral celebrity posts multiple posts, the loadf can be shared by multiple database instances.\n     9. Considering viral contents are posted by celebrities, we can think of a strategy to have bunch of instances for celebrity posts. \n         Those instances needs a very high read throughput. Based on estimations from peak day, we can think of adding more replicas to those celebrity shard instances.\n     10. If adding replicas is not making a certain host worn out, we can also think of migrating that post to a lesser load database or add more replicas.\n     11. For database having posts of non-celebrity, we can shard by user_id but we might not need replicas for the same.\n    \n   \n    ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
